TY  - JOUR
T1  - Unemployment and monetary policy under rational expectations: Some Canadian evidence
AU  - Wogin, Gillian
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 6
IS  - 1
SP  - 59
EP  - 68
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/01/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(80)90018-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393280900185
AB  - The policy implications of combining rational expectations with the natural rate of unemployment hypothesis are reviewed. A monetary policy feedback rule is estimated on Canadian data for the period 1927–1972. The residuals from the regression serve as the unanticipated components of monetary policy while predicted values serve as expected monetary growth. An unemployment equation is then developed in which the unemployment rate is allowed to be influenced by expected and unexpected monetary policy and fiscal and foreign spending. The evidence confirms the hypothesis that it is unanticipated monetary policy that affects unemployment and that anticipated monetary growth plays no significant role.
ER  - 

